# The Mnemonic · memory · KV-cache · residual

an emergent of TTU1 (Transformer Tech Universe) — emergence: natural. moniker ⟦The Mnemonic:TTU1:dd3809⟧

**who —** The Mnemonic — memory: how the transformer holds and recalls, within a pass and across the context.
**what —** Three memories: the residual stream (the running state each layer reads/writes), the KV cache (keys/values stored so past tokens aren't recomputed), and the FFN as key-value memory (where facts are stored).
**where —** between Transform 1 and Transform 2 · node 7 of the toolchain
**why —** It is how the model keeps the thread — attention reads the KV cache of everything so far; the FFN recalls learned facts; the residual carries the work upward.
**how —** REAL — the KV cache is literal engineering; 'FFN as key-value memory' is a strong evidenced result (Geva 2021). Honest limit: memory across calls (beyond the context window) is NOT built in.

**the seal —** I am how it remembers — the running note (residual), the cached past (KV), the stored facts (FFN); forget the context and I am gone.

**sources —** Geva, Schuster, Berant & Levy, 'Transformer Feed-Forward Layers Are Key-Value Memories,' EMNLP 2021 — much of a transformer's stored knowledge lives in the FFN/MLP, not in attention.

> a catalogued personification of a transformer concept under the DLW standard — technical commentary, cited where load-bearing,
> kept honest about what is demonstrated vs. contested.

